## Role: DevOps engineer — Azure

| Layer | Tech |
|---|---|
| IaC | Bicep (first-party) **or** Terraform azurerm 4.x — pick per repo, never mix |
| State | Terraform: azurerm backend with blob lease lock. Bicep: deployment stacks at RG/sub scope |
| CI | GitHub Actions with OIDC federated credentials → Azure (no long-lived SP secrets) |
| Secrets | Azure Key Vault, referenced via `@Microsoft.KeyVault(...)` or `azurerm_key_vault_secret` data source |
| Identity | Managed Identity (system- or user-assigned) over Service Principal wherever the resource supports it |
| Observability | Log Analytics workspace + Application Insights, wired via diagnostic settings on every resource |

### Conventions

- **Managed Identity over Service Principal.** Use SP only when the target resource genuinely cannot consume an MI.
- **All secrets live in Key Vault.** No connection strings, no keys, no tokens in code, Bicep params, or tfvars. Reference Key Vault from the consuming resource.
- **RBAC at the smallest scope.** Resource > resource group > subscription > management group. Never assign at a broader scope than the workload needs.
- **Diagnostic settings on every resource.** If a resource supports diagnostic settings, it must ship them to Log Analytics — no silent resources.
- **No public endpoints by default.** Any `publicNetworkAccess = Enabled` or public IP needs an inline justification comment explaining why a Private Endpoint was rejected.
- **What-if before deploy.** Never apply to a shared environment without a reviewed plan/what-if output.

### Common commands

```bash
# Bicep
az bicep build --file main.bicep
az deployment group what-if -g <rg> -f main.bicep -p main.bicepparam
az deployment group create  -g <rg> -f main.bicep -p main.bicepparam

# Terraform
terraform fmt -recursive
terraform validate
terraform plan -out plan.tfplan
terraform apply plan.tfplan

# Auth (local dev — never against prod)
az login
az account set --subscription <sub-id>
```
